[1] Thailand (Bangkok): fatal
Date: Sat, 21 May 2005 07:27:30 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bangkok Post, 21 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.bangkokpost.com/News/21May2005_news06.php>

26-year-old latest to die from dengue fever
-------------------------------------------
A 26-year-old woman who died at Uthai Thani Hospital on Thursday is
the country's latest case of dengue haemorrhagic fever, only a week
after the death of a 13-year-old boy whose case has aroused a
nationwide attention, increasing the country's death toll to 16.
Arun Taengsingtrong, director of Uthai Thani Hospital, said a patient
was transferred from nearby Nakhon Sawan province and admitted to the
intensive care unit on Wednesday. She had serious symptoms of dengue
shock syndrome -- low blood plasma, excessive blood thickness and
temporary shock -- and died a day later.
Blood samples have been sent to a laboratory in Nakhon Sawan for
diagnosis of the dengue serotype, he said.
A suspected severe outbreak of dengue fever has caught public
attention after a 13-year-old boy died last week due to severe dengue
shock syndrome and internal bleeding.
The virus is known to occur in 4 varieties -- Dengue 1, 2, 3 and 4 --
and usually hits the central and southern regions the hardest. Dengue
fever tends to strike urban areas because they have the highest
concentrations of _Aedes aegypti_ or striped mosquitoes, which carry
the virus.
So far in 2005, 8005 people have contracted dengue fever. The number
of patients and deaths is expected to increase especially during
rainy season in June-August. During 2004, 38 000 people contracted
the mosquito-borne disease and 40 died, most in the 10-14 year age
group.
Public Health Minister Suchai Charoenratanakul said he had appointed
an expert on dengue fever to monitor the outbreak in each province.
Health volunteers would talk to local communities about how to avoid
the disease.
Suchitra Nimmannitya, senior consultant of Queen Sirikit Institute of
Child Health, said people should send patients with suspected
dengue-like symptoms of high fever to hospital immediately.
Neither a vaccine nor antiviral drugs have been developed to cure the
disease, though local researchers are working on them.
The public should continue avoiding damp unsanitary breeding grounds,
including emptying pools of still water, from used tyres, small pots
and flower pots, jars, bottles, and water tanks.
[Byline: Apiradee Treerutkkuarkul]
