[3] Thailand (Phuket)
Date: Tue 24 May 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: MCOT TNA English News, 24 May 2005 [edited]
<http://etna.mcot.net/query.php?nid=38780>

Dengue cases double in Phuket
-----------------------------
Thailand's southern island resort of Phuket today [24 May 2005]
launched a concerted campaign to destroy mosquitoes responsible for
spreading dengue fever, after a discovery of a 2-fold rise in the
number of dengue cases since last year [2004].
Led by Deputy Phuket Governor Suphachai Yuwaboon and the chief
provincial public health official, the campaign kicked off this
morning with pleas to the public to help in the fight against the
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
Members of the public taking part in the launch held banners and
paraded around the town stating their commitment to destroying
mosquito larvae.
According to Dr. Wanchai Satyawuthiphong, the island province's chief
public health official, there are currently 68 confirmed cases of
dengue fever on the island, with another 340 patients waiting
diagnosis.
Phuket has the 9th highest number of dengue cases in the country [but does
not figure in the list of 10 most affected provinces in the post above. -
Mod.JW], and more than double the number it had last year [2004]. However,
the chief public health officer stressed that no one had yet died of the
condition, which has become a matter of national concern this year [2005].
