[5] Indonesia (Jakarta)
Date: Tue 24 May 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>, Alfonso Rodriguez
<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Bernama.com - Malaysian National News Agency, 24 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com.my/bernama/v3/news.php?id=135951>

Dengue hemorrhagic fever fast spreading in Indonesia
----------------------------------------------------
Dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) is spreading fast in Indonesia, with
7339 cases and 40 deaths reported in Jakarta between January 2005 and
last Sunday [22 May 2005].
A local newspaper quoted the Health Department as saying that the
number of DHF cases would reach its peak in May and June, when
climatic changes take place with intermittent rain. During the 2
months, many water catchment areas would become _Aedes_ mosquito
breeding grounds, it said. In Bandung, West Java residents were
reminded to be wary against DHF following the transition from rainy
to drought season, it said.
West Java Health Department head Yudi Prayudha said dengue cases
might rise as the people did not bother to clean up areas with
stagnant waters. So far, 895 cases and 7 deaths have been detected in
Bandung, he said. In Bogor, he said, 350 cases with 9 deaths have
been reported, while in Padang, Sumatera, 249 people have been taken
ill with 3 deaths from January 2005 till now.
