[6] Australia (Townsville)
Date: Tue 24 May 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Townsville Bulletin, Australia, 24 May 2005 [edited]
<http://townsvillebulletin.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,7034,15386957%
255E14787,00.html>
Dengue breeding places spotted
------------------------------
Health inspectors have discovered large numbers of dengue mosquitoes
in the Currajong area.
Staff from the Townsville and Thuringowa city councils are working
closely with mosquito control experts from the Tropical Public Health
Unit to conduct house-to-house inspections and mosquito eradication.
Experts hope they can contain the dengue outbreak which has so far
affected 4 people, with several more cases suspected.
3 cases have been confirmed in Currajong and one in Kirwan. There are
also 2 suspected cases in Kirwan and Railway Estate. Acting director
of environmental health with Queensland's Tropical Public Health Unit
Damien Farrington said it was vital that twin cities residents took
immediate steps to prevent the outbreak from escalating.
Dengue victim and Townsville's Deputy Mayor Councilor Ann Bunnell
urged residents to do all they could to stop the outbreak from
spreading. "Dengue is the [worst] illness I have ever had in my life,"
Cr. Bunnell said. "My husband and daughter got it at the same time;
my daughter got a serious blood problem from it. We were very ill,
terribly ill." Cr. Bunnell said she believed she was still
experiencing some health problems as a result of the disease. "It can
be fatal. It is different [from] Ross River fever; the mosquito which
carries Ross River can travel 40 km while the dengue mosquito can
only travel 200 m. So if you get it, it has come from your own home
or the people you visit."
Mr. Farrington said that, to protect themselves, residents had to
check their yard for mosquito breeding. "Tip out, flush out, throw
away or store dry any containers holding water in which mosquitoes
can breed, such as old tires, buckets, toys, pot plant bases, and
blocked roof gutters," he said. "Use insect repellent: wear personal
repellent if you are being bitten during the day, and use surface
insect spray, mozzie [mosquito] zappers and coils around the house."
People with symptoms of dengue -- such as fever, headache, rash, loss
of appetite, vomiting and diarrhea, and fatigue -- should see a
doctor immediately. The serious form of the disease, dengue
hemorrhagic fever, can be fatal, especially in young children.
[Byline: Vikki Campion]
